Step 8 – SSH (Secure Shell) & Remote Server Management

If Linux is your operating system, SSH is your doorway into every server.

Almost all DevOps work happens remotely:

Connecting to cloud servers.
Managing EC2 instances.
Deploying applications.
Running Ansible.
Configuring Docker hosts.
Managing Kubernetes nodes.
🎯 Learning Objectives

By the end of this step, you'll be able to:

Understand SSH.
Connect to remote servers.
Generate SSH keys.
Configure passwordless login.
Copy files using SCP.
Sync files using rsync.
Secure SSH access.
Troubleshoot SSH failures.
1. What is SSH?

SSH (Secure Shell) allows you to securely access another machine over a network.

Example:

Your Laptop
     │
     │ SSH
     ▼
Linux Server

Instead of physically sitting in front of the server, you control it remotely.

2. Basic SSH Connection
ssh username@server_ip

Example:

ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.100

or:

ssh ubuntu@10.0.0.15
3. Connect Using a Different Port

If SSH runs on port 2222:

ssh -p 2222 ubuntu@192.168.1.100
4. First Connection

The first time you connect:

The authenticity of host can't be established.
Are you sure you want to continue connecting?

Type:

yes

Linux stores the server fingerprint in:

~/.ssh/known_hosts
5. Generate SSH Keys

This is the preferred authentication method in DevOps.

Generate a key:

ssh-keygen

Press Enter to accept defaults.

Files created:

~/.ssh/id_rsa
~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

or on newer systems:

~/.ssh/id_ed25519
~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
6. Public vs Private Key
Private Key
id_ed25519

Keep it secret.

Never share it.

Public Key
id_ed25519.pub

Safe to share with servers.

Think of it like:

Public Key  = Lock
Private Key = Key
7. Copy Public Key to a Server
ssh-copy-id ubuntu@192.168.1.100

After this:

ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.100

No password required.

This is called passwordless authentication.

8. Manually Add Keys

View your public key:

cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

Add it to:

~/.ssh/authorized_keys

on the remote server.

9. SSH Configuration File

Create:

nano ~/.ssh/config

Example:

Host prod
    HostName 192.168.1.100
    User ubuntu
    Port 22

Now connect using:

ssh prod

This becomes extremely useful when managing many servers.

10. Copy Files Using SCP

Copy local file to server:

scp file.txt ubuntu@192.168.1.100:/home/ubuntu/

Copy from server:

scp ubuntu@192.168.1.100:/home/ubuntu/file.txt .
11. Copy Directories
scp -r project ubuntu@192.168.1.100:/home/ubuntu/
12. Sync Files Using rsync

Install:

sudo apt install rsync

Sync directories:

rsync -av project/ ubuntu@192.168.1.100:/home/ubuntu/project/

Advantages:

Faster than SCP for repeated transfers.
Copies only changed files.
Widely used in deployments.
13. Verify SSH Service

Check:

systemctl status ssh

or:

systemctl status sshd

Depending on the distribution.

14. Check SSH Port
ss -tulpn | grep :22

Example:

LISTEN 0 128 0.0.0.0:22

SSH is listening.

15. Important SSH Configuration

Configuration file:

/etc/ssh/sshd_config

Common settings:

Disable root login:

PermitRootLogin no

Disable password authentication:

PasswordAuthentication no

Change SSH port:

Port 2222

After changes:

sudo systemctl restart ssh
16. Check SSH Logs

Ubuntu:

journalctl -u ssh

or:

grep ssh /var/log/auth.log
17. Test SSH Connectivity

Check port availability:

nc -zv 192.168.1.100 22
