Interview Questions
What is SSH?
SSH (Secure Shell) is a secure network protocol used to connect and manage remote Linux/Unix servers over an encrypted connection.
Uses:
Remote server login
Execute commands remotely
Transfer files securely
Manage cloud servers (AWS, Azure, etc.)
Example:
ssh username@server_ip

What is the default SSH port?
The default SSH port is:
Port 22
SSH server listens on port 22 by default.
Check:
ss -tulpn | grep :22

What is the difference between a public key and a private key?
Public Key                          	  Private Key
Shared with servers	                      Kept secret on your machine
Stored on remote server	                  Stored on client machine
Used to encrypt/verify authentication	  Used to prove your identity
Can be copied safely	                  Never share it
Example:
Private Key:
~/.ssh/id_rsa
Public Key:
~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

What does ssh-copy-id do?
ssh-copy-id copies your public key to a remote server's authorized_keys file.
Example:
ssh-copy-id user@server_ip
It adds:
~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
content into:
~/.ssh/authorized_keys
After this, you can login without entering a password.

What is authorized_keys?
authorized_keys is a file on the SSH server that stores the public keys of users allowed to login.
Location:
~/.ssh/authorized_keys
Example:
Server
 |
 └── ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
          |
          └── Client public key

When you connect:
Server checks your public key
Matches it with authorized_keys
Allows login if valid

What is the purpose of ~/.ssh/config?
~/.ssh/config stores custom SSH connection settings.
It helps avoid typing long SSH commands.
Example:
File:
nano ~/.ssh/config
Configuration:
Host myserver
    HostName 192.168.1.10
    User devops
    Port 22
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa
Now instead of:
ssh devops@192.168.1.10
You can use:
ssh myserver

What is the difference between scp and rsync?
scp	                                              rsync
Secure copy	                                      Remote synchronization tool
Copies complete files every time	              Copies only changed data
Simple file transfer	                          Faster for large data
No sync capability	                              Maintains directory synchronization
Example:
scp:
scp file.txt user@server:/tmp/
rsync:
rsync -avz folder/ user@server:/backup/

How do you check whether SSH is running?
Using systemctl:
systemctl status ssh
or:
systemctl status sshd
Check port:
ss -tulpn | grep :22
Check process:
ps aux | grep sshd

What causes "Permission denied (publickey)" errors?
Common reasons:
Public key is not copied to server:
ssh-copy-id user@server
Wrong private key:
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa user@server
Wrong permissions:
Client:
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa
Server:
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
SSH configuration disables key authentication.
Check:
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Look for:
PubkeyAuthentication yes

Why is key-based authentication preferred over passwords?
Key-based authentication is preferred because:
✅ More secure
✅ Resistant to brute-force attacks
✅ No password transmission
✅ Supports automation (DevOps tools, CI/CD pipelines)
✅ Better for server-to-server communication
Example DevOps usage:
Jenkins → Server deployment
Ansible → Remote server management
GitHub Actions → Cloud deployment

